# AI Development Rules  ## Project Context  Before making architectural or implementation decisions, consult the relevant documentation under `docs/`.  Priority order:  1. `docs/architecture.md` 2. `docs/decisions.md` 3. `docs/project.md` 4. `docs/backlog.md` (only for planning tasks)  Do not assume architecture that is not documented or present in the codebase.  ---  ## Implementation Principles  * Prefer small, focused changes. * Implement only the requested task. * Do not refactor unrelated systems. * Do not introduce new architectural patterns unless justified. * Follow existing project conventions. * Keep classes focused on a single responsibility. * Favor composition over large monolithic classes.  ---  ## Before Coding  For medium or large tasks:  1. Analyze the existing implementation. 2. Explain the proposed approach. 3. Identify files that will be modified. 4. Wait for approval if the task affects multiple systems.  ---  ## During Implementation  * Reuse existing systems where appropriate. * Avoid duplicate logic. * Minimize coupling between systems. * Prefer object pooling for frequently spawned gameplay objects. * Avoid unnecessary allocations in gameplay loops.  ---  ## After Implementation  Always provide:  ### Summary  * What was implemented * Files modified  ### Review  * Potential risks * Edge cases * Follow-up improvements  ### Testing  Suggest manual tests to validate the implementation.  ---  ## Documentation  If a completed task changes architecture, gameplay systems, or project decisions:  * Suggest updates to relevant files under `docs/`. * Do not silently modify documentation unless explicitly requested.  ---  ## Planning Requests  When asked to implement a feature:  1. Break the work into small tasks. 2. Present the task list. 3. Recommend the next task to implement. 4. Avoid implementing the entire feature in one step unless explicitly requested.
